# Day 1 – C Programming Bridge Course (MIT MSIS)

This folder contains the foundational C programs completed on **Day 1** of the Bridge Course at **Manipal School of Information Sciences (MSIS)**.

---

## ✅ Topics Covered

- Function implementation
- Arithmetic operations
- ASCII manipulation
- Conditionals
- Bitwise operations
- Header and source file separation
- Usage of `assert()` for testing

---

## 📁 Files Included

| File Name           | Description                                      |
|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| `main.c`            | Main driver program to test all functionalities  |
| `day1_operation.c`  | Contains the implementation of all functions     |
| `day1.h`            | Header file with function prototypes             |

---

## 🔧 Functions Implemented

- `int add(int x, int y)` – Add two integers
- `int sub(int x, int y)` – Subtract two integers
- `int is_even(int n)` – Check if a number is even
- `int reverse_number(int n)` – Reverse a number
- `char convertchar(char c)` – Convert uppercase to lowercase
- `void convert_string(char* str)` – Convert string to lowercase
- `float area_of_circle(int r)` – Calculate area of a circle
- `int find_number_chara(char x, char y)` – Difference in ASCII (count between characters)
- `float ctof(int n)` – Convert Celsius to Fahrenheit
- `int check_leap(int year)` – Check if a year is a leap year
- `int power_n(int n)` – Calculate 2^n using bitwise shift
- `int check_num_char(char s)` – Check if a character is a digit
- `int random_sum()` – Generate 2 random numbers and return their sum

---

## 🧪 Test Strategy

Some functions are tested using `assert()` in `main.c` for correctness.

---

## 💬 Notes

- The code uses standard C conventions.
- The structure separates logic into header (`.h`) and implementation (`.c`) files.
- Uses ASCII logic to minimize conditionals where possible.

